408→                           Erdős and Szemerédi proved that\[n^{1/2} \ll h(n) \ll n^{1-c}\]for some constant $c&gt;0$. The upper bound has been improved to $h(n)\ll n^{2/3}$ by Freiman and Lev. A proof of these bounds can be found in a paper of Granville and Roesler <a href="#cite-GrRo99-539" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('GrRo99','539'); return false;">[GrRo99]</a>.<br><br>Granville and Roesler also reformulate this problem as one in combinatorial geometry: given $A\subseteq \mathbb{Z}^d$ of size $n$ what is the minimum size possible of\[\{ \delta(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}) : \mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}\in A\}\]where $\delta(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})$ has $i$th coordinate $\max(0,a_i-b_i)$. Using this formulation that obtain improved lower bounds in fixed small dimension $d$.
